[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":640},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F11\u002Fjs-from-zero-26-es6-let-const\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F11\u002Fjs-from-zero-26-es6-let-const\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F11\u002Fjs-from-zero-26-es6-let-const\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F11\u002Fjs-from-zero-26-es6-let-const\u002F":615,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F11\u002Fjs-from-zero-26-es6-let-const\u002F":624},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20191011\u002F1172259820\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":597,"date":598,"description":599,"extension":600,"lang":601,"meta":602,"navigation":603,"path":604,"readingMinutes":605,"seo":606,"standalone":607,"stem":608,"tags":609,"tldr":612,"updated":598,"url":613,"__hash__":614},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjs-from-zero-26-es6-let-const.md","ES6 let & const: Why You Should Stop Using var (And What the Temporal Dead Zone Is)","1002169809",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":589},"minimark",[11,16,29,33,45,61,75,119,122,147,150,152,166,227,238,245,256,308,318,324,349,351,361,400,413,442,449,454,464,470,473,477,499,524,534,539,550,556,564,573,578,582,585],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19,20,24,25,28],"p",{},"Day 26 of getting reincarnated into JS land, and from here on we're getting into ES6. First up is ES6's ",[21,22,23],"code",{},"let"," and ",[21,26,27],{},"const",".",[12,30,32],{"id":31},"let-const","let & const",[17,34,35,36,24,38,40,41,44],{},"So what are ",[21,37,23],{},[21,39,27],{},"? Normally when we declare a variable we use ",[21,42,43],{},"var",". Then ES6 came along and added two new ways to declare variables, and honestly they fix a bunch of bugs you'd otherwise run into during development. The quick way to think about them:",[46,47,48,56],"ul",{},[49,50,51,53,54],"li",{},[21,52,23],{}," — pretty much like the old ",[21,55,43],{},[49,57,58,60],{},[21,59,27],{}," — a constant, meaning a value that can't change",[17,62,63,64,24,66,68,69,71,72,74],{},"If you're not totally sure about the difference between ",[21,65,23],{},[21,67,27],{}," when you're coding, a good starting move is to just swap your ",[21,70,43],{}," over to ",[21,73,23],{},". Once you're comfortable with how the two differ, you can fine-tune from there. So if your original code looked like this:",[76,77,82],"pre",{"className":78,"code":79,"language":80,"meta":81,"style":81},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","var a = 1;\nconsole.log(a);\n","js","",[21,83,84,106],{"__ignoreMap":81},[85,86,89,92,96,99,103],"span",{"class":87,"line":88},"line",1,[85,90,43],{"class":91},"sWyjQ",[85,93,95],{"class":94},"sMAXC"," a ",[85,97,98],{"class":91},"=",[85,100,102],{"class":101},"sCcAr"," 1",[85,104,105],{"class":94},";\n",[85,107,109,112,116],{"class":87,"line":108},2,[85,110,111],{"class":94},"console.",[85,113,115],{"class":114},"sj_SG","log",[85,117,118],{"class":94},"(a);\n",[17,120,121],{},"You can change it to this:",[76,123,125],{"className":78,"code":124,"language":80,"meta":81,"style":81},"let a = 1;\nconsole.log(a);\n",[21,126,127,139],{"__ignoreMap":81},[85,128,129,131,133,135,137],{"class":87,"line":88},[85,130,23],{"class":91},[85,132,95],{"class":94},[85,134,98],{"class":91},[85,136,102],{"class":101},[85,138,105],{"class":94},[85,140,141,143,145],{"class":87,"line":108},[85,142,111],{"class":94},[85,144,115],{"class":114},[85,146,118],{"class":94},[17,148,149],{},"The difference between those two is tiny.",[12,151,23],{"id":23},[17,153,154,155,24,157,159,160,162,163,165],{},"I just said ",[21,156,23],{},[21,158,43],{}," aren't that different, so you might be thinking \"if they're basically the same, why bother switching to ",[21,161,23],{},"?\" The thing is, declaring variables with ",[21,164,43],{}," can cause some problems:",[76,167,169],{"className":78,"code":168,"language":80,"meta":81,"style":81},"var a = 1;\nif(true) {\n  var a = 2;\n}\nconsole.log(a);\n",[21,170,171,183,197,212,218],{"__ignoreMap":81},[85,172,173,175,177,179,181],{"class":87,"line":88},[85,174,43],{"class":91},[85,176,95],{"class":94},[85,178,98],{"class":91},[85,180,102],{"class":101},[85,182,105],{"class":94},[85,184,185,188,191,194],{"class":87,"line":108},[85,186,187],{"class":91},"if",[85,189,190],{"class":94},"(",[85,192,193],{"class":101},"true",[85,195,196],{"class":94},") {\n",[85,198,200,203,205,207,210],{"class":87,"line":199},3,[85,201,202],{"class":91},"  var",[85,204,95],{"class":94},[85,206,98],{"class":91},[85,208,209],{"class":101}," 2",[85,211,105],{"class":94},[85,213,215],{"class":87,"line":214},4,[85,216,217],{"class":94},"}\n",[85,219,221,223,225],{"class":87,"line":220},5,[85,222,111],{"class":94},[85,224,115],{"class":114},[85,226,118],{"class":94},[17,228,229,230,233,234,237],{},"You'll notice the global variable ",[21,231,232],{},"a"," got changed to ",[21,235,236],{},"2"," here:",[17,239,240],{},[241,242],"img",{"alt":243,"src":244},"global a changed to 2","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002Fe0c9GYn.png",[17,246,247,248,252,253,255],{},"This is what's called ",[249,250,251],"strong",{},"variable pollution",". So what about ",[21,254,23],{},"? Let's rewrite the example above:",[76,257,259],{"className":78,"code":258,"language":80,"meta":81,"style":81},"let a = 1;\nif(true) {\n  let a = 2;\n}\nconsole.log(a);\n",[21,260,261,273,283,296,300],{"__ignoreMap":81},[85,262,263,265,267,269,271],{"class":87,"line":88},[85,264,23],{"class":91},[85,266,95],{"class":94},[85,268,98],{"class":91},[85,270,102],{"class":101},[85,272,105],{"class":94},[85,274,275,277,279,281],{"class":87,"line":108},[85,276,187],{"class":91},[85,278,190],{"class":94},[85,280,193],{"class":101},[85,282,196],{"class":94},[85,284,285,288,290,292,294],{"class":87,"line":199},[85,286,287],{"class":91},"  let",[85,289,95],{"class":94},[85,291,98],{"class":91},[85,293,209],{"class":101},[85,295,105],{"class":94},[85,297,298],{"class":87,"line":214},[85,299,217],{"class":94},[85,301,302,304,306],{"class":87,"line":220},[85,303,111],{"class":94},[85,305,115],{"class":114},[85,307,118],{"class":94},[17,309,310,311,313,314,317],{},"You'll find ",[21,312,232],{}," is still 1 — it didn't get affected by the inner ",[21,315,316],{},"let a = 2",":",[17,319,320],{},[241,321],{"alt":322,"src":323},"a is still 1","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002F8Z3jHd2.png",[17,325,326,327,329,330,333,334,336,337,339,340,342,343,345,346,348],{},"So we can draw a conclusion: ",[21,328,23],{}," is a block-scoped variable. \"Block\" means the chunk inside the curly braces (",[21,331,332],{},"{ }","), so a variable declared with ",[21,335,23],{}," only lives inside those braces. And ",[21,338,43],{},"? ",[21,341,43],{}," is a function-scoped variable, meaning its range only stretches within the function. But to put it more precisely: ",[21,344,23],{}," has block scope, and ",[21,347,43],{}," has function scope.",[12,350,27],{"id":27},[17,352,353,354,356,357,360],{},"Now what about ",[21,355,27],{},"? Let's talk about what a constant is first. A constant is a ",[249,358,359],{},"fixed, unchanging value",". With regular variables, we can keep reassigning them over and over:",[76,362,364],{"className":78,"code":363,"language":80,"meta":81,"style":81},"var a = 1;\na = 2;\na = 3;\n",[21,365,366,378,389],{"__ignoreMap":81},[85,367,368,370,372,374,376],{"class":87,"line":88},[85,369,43],{"class":91},[85,371,95],{"class":94},[85,373,98],{"class":91},[85,375,102],{"class":101},[85,377,105],{"class":94},[85,379,380,383,385,387],{"class":87,"line":108},[85,381,382],{"class":94},"a ",[85,384,98],{"class":91},[85,386,209],{"class":101},[85,388,105],{"class":94},[85,390,391,393,395,398],{"class":87,"line":199},[85,392,382],{"class":94},[85,394,98],{"class":91},[85,396,397],{"class":101}," 3",[85,399,105],{"class":94},[17,401,402,403,406,407,409,410,412],{},"The catch with this kind of declaration is that you might ",[249,404,405],{},"accidentally overwrite a value you didn't mean to touch",". So if your value is fixed and won't change, you can use ",[21,408,27],{},". And if you declare a variable with ",[21,411,27],{}," and then try to change it anyway?",[76,414,416],{"className":78,"code":415,"language":80,"meta":81,"style":81},"const a = 1;\na = 2;\n",[21,417,418,432],{"__ignoreMap":81},[85,419,420,422,425,428,430],{"class":87,"line":88},[85,421,27],{"class":91},[85,423,424],{"class":101}," a",[85,426,427],{"class":91}," =",[85,429,102],{"class":101},[85,431,105],{"class":94},[85,433,434,436,438,440],{"class":87,"line":108},[85,435,382],{"class":94},[85,437,98],{"class":91},[85,439,209],{"class":101},[85,441,105],{"class":94},[17,443,444,445,448],{},"You'll get an error message: ",[21,446,447],{},"Assignment to constant variable."," In short, it's telling you \"I'm not letting you change this constant\":",[17,450,451],{},[241,452],{"alt":447,"src":453},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FHUSvIVF.png",[17,455,456,457,460,461,463],{},"One last thing to watch out for here. When you declare a variable, writing ",[21,458,459],{},"let a;"," won't throw an error. But ",[21,462,27],{}," has to be given a value — if you don't assign an initial value, you'll get an error:",[17,465,466],{},[241,467],{"alt":468,"src":469},"Missing initializer in const declaration","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FZamj3kq.png",[17,471,472],{},"Basically it's saying \"you forgot to give me a value.\"",[12,474,476],{"id":475},"a-bit-more","A bit more",[17,478,479,480,24,482,484,485,24,487,489,490,24,492,494,495,498],{},"Last, let me touch on hoisting with ",[21,481,23],{},[21,483,27],{},". We already covered hoisting earlier, but what about ES6's ",[21,486,23],{},[21,488,27],{}," — do they get hoisted? Actually, ",[21,491,23],{},[21,493,27],{}," don't have hoisting. Instead there's another concept called the ",[249,496,497],{},"temporal dead zone",". What does that mean? Let's look at some code:",[76,500,502],{"className":78,"code":501,"language":80,"meta":81,"style":81},"console.log(a);\nlet a = 1;\n",[21,503,504,512],{"__ignoreMap":81},[85,505,506,508,510],{"class":87,"line":88},[85,507,111],{"class":94},[85,509,115],{"class":114},[85,511,118],{"class":94},[85,513,514,516,518,520,522],{"class":87,"line":108},[85,515,23],{"class":91},[85,517,95],{"class":94},[85,519,98],{"class":91},[85,521,102],{"class":101},[85,523,105],{"class":94},[17,525,526,527,530,531,317],{},"Normally you'd expect to get ",[21,528,529],{},"undefined",", but with ES6 variable declarations you'll get ",[21,532,533],{},"Uncaught ReferenceError: Cannot access 'a' before initialization",[17,535,536],{},[241,537],{"alt":533,"src":538},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FUT4ckUo.png",[17,540,541,542,24,544,546,547,549],{},"What does that mean? In short: \"you can't use this variable until I've run this line.\" The MDN docs also explain that ",[21,543,23],{},[21,545,27],{}," don't have hoisting — instead there's the so-called ",[249,548,497],{},". Here's an excerpt from MDN:",[551,552,553],"blockquote",{},[17,554,555],{},"In ECMAScript 2015, let bindings are not subject to Variable Hoisting, which means that let declarations do not move to the top of the current execution context. Referencing the variable in the block before the initialization results in a ReferenceError (contrary to a variable declared with var, which will just have the undefined value). The variable is in a \"temporal dead zone\" from the start of the block until the initialization is processed.",[17,557,558],{},[232,559,563],{"href":560,"rel":561},"https:\u002F\u002Fdeveloper.mozilla.org\u002Fen-US\u002Fdocs\u002FWeb\u002FJavaScript\u002FReference\u002FStatements\u002Flet#Temporal_Dead_Zone_and_errors_with_let",[562],"nofollow","Original source",[17,565,566,567,569,570,572],{},"That MDN excerpt only talks about ",[21,568,23],{},", but ",[21,571,27],{}," works the same way — so when you try it out, you'll get the same result:",[17,574,575],{},[241,576],{"alt":533,"src":577},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FE9qDMMa.png",[12,579,581],{"id":580},"wrapping-up","Wrapping up",[17,583,584],{},"In the next post, RE: Starting Life Again Learning JS Day 27, I'll cover ES6 arrow functions.",[586,587,588],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html pre.shiki code .sCcAr, html code.shiki .sCcAr{--shiki-default:#91CBFF}html pre.shiki code .sj_SG, html code.shiki .sj_SG{--shiki-default:#DBB7FF}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}",{"title":81,"searchDepth":108,"depth":108,"links":590},[591,592,593,594,595,596],{"id":14,"depth":108,"text":15},{"id":31,"depth":108,"text":32},{"id":23,"depth":108,"text":23},{"id":27,"depth":108,"text":27},{"id":475,"depth":108,"text":476},{"id":580,"depth":108,"text":581},"JavaScript","2019-10-11 08:40:44","Day 26 of my reincarnated JS journey, and we're finally getting into ES6. First up: `let` and `const`. We'll look at how they fix variable pollution, why `const` won't let you reassign, and that weird thing called the temporal dead zone that trips people up when they think `let` and `const` get hoisted.","md","en",{},true,"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002Fjs-from-zero-26-es6-let-const","4",{"title":6,"description":599},false,"en\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjs-from-zero-26-es6-let-const",[597,610,611],"RE：從零開始的學習 JS 生活","第 11 屆 iT邦幫忙鐵人賽",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F11\u002Fjs-from-zero-26-es6-let-const\u002F","rK7mnc4K3RfUBRyQrFzu2gRnBTXcimYQj7-fxOB6bGE",{"newer":616,"older":620},{"url":617,"title":618,"date":619},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F12\u002Fjs-from-zero-ep27-es6-arrow-functions\u002F","ES6 Arrow Functions: Less Typing, But Watch Out for `this`","2019-10-12 08:30:13",{"url":621,"title":622,"date":623},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F10\u002Fjs-from-zero-25-callback-hell\u002F","Learning JS From Zero (Day 25): What Exactly Is Callback Hell?","2019-10-10 05:06:52",[625,630,635],{"url":626,"title":627,"date":628,"readingMinutes":629},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2026\u002F03\u002F10\u002Fweb-crypto-api-encryption-guide\u002F","No crypto Package, No Node.js — The Web Crypto API Does It All in the Browser","2026-03-10 09:45:08","9",{"url":631,"title":632,"date":633,"readingMinutes":634},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2025\u002F12\u002F08\u002Fjquery-why-it-declined\u002F","jQuery Was Once King — So Why Did It Fall Off?","2025-12-08 21:35:24","7",{"url":636,"title":637,"date":638,"readingMinutes":639},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2025\u002F12\u002F05\u002Fjavascript-generator-functions\u002F","What Are JavaScript Generator Functions (function*)? The Function You Can Pause and Resume","2025-12-05 13:40:31","5",1784013060282]